ing of parameters. One solution could be to return `UNSET` from `Parameter.get_default` specifically when the default is the internal `UNSET` sentinel instead of returning `None`. \n\nAnother idea is to modify `Parameter.handle_parse_result` or `Option.handle_parse_result` so that it only normalizes `UNSET` to `None` when setting `ctx.params` for exposed values after all parameters have been processed. I'm curious if that would work effectively.**Evaluating default parameters**\n\nI'm thinking about how shared destination names among parameters function. It seems that the first default value is going to take precedence. If a parameter has a default set to an internal sentinel value indicating it's unset, that should allow later defaults to take precedence without causing any issues. It's fascinating how these defaults operate and can impact the overall behavior. I want to ensure I keep this in mind for future reference!**Considering default parameters**\n\nI’m looking into how to handle default parameters in a function call. If `default_value` is unset, I think we should skip setting it in `kwargs`. For other parameters, if they don’t exist in `kwargs` but have `expose_value`, we might want to set them to None. But then I wonder about required parameters—if they're missing, I guess the parser won’t call the command. So, I need to think about making a second pass to deal with any exposed values not in `kwargs`.**Assessing parameter defaults**\n\nI’m considering how to handle situations where the parameter name isn’t shared, but the default is set to UNSET. In these cases, the callback would receive None, which maintains consistency. I believe we'll need a two-pass approach in `Context.invoke`, possibly involving `Context.lookup_default`. The goal is to ensure minimal changes while implementing default lookup and normalization. I should also look for existing tests around `default_map` and shared flag parameters and design a new one to cover this scenario.**Evaluating